  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Duration and spirit of Joram's reign. - These verses agree with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:17-22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with the exception of some immaterial divergences, and have been commented upon in the remarks on that passage. - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 21:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the thought is somewhat otherwise expressed than in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : \"Jahve would not destroy the house of David, because of the covenant that He had made with David;\" instead of, \"He would not destroy Judah because of David His servant, as He had said.\" Instead of לבניו ניר לו לתת we have in the Chronicle וּלבניו ניר לו לתת, to give him a lamp, and that in respect of his sons, w being inserted before לבניו to bring the idea more prominently forward. In regard to שׂריו עם, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 21:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", instead of צעירה, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see on 2 Kings c. cit. At the end of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 21:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the words, \"and the people fled to their tents\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), whereby the notice of Joram's attempt to bring Edom again under his sway, which is in itself obscure enough, becomes yet more obscure. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
